window.__QUIZ_DATA__=[{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2006>SECTION A>1>a","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : SEQUENCES AND SERIES","question":"The sum of the 2nd and 5t terms of an arithmetic progression (A.P) is 42. If the difference between the 6th and 3rd terms is 12, find the:    common difference","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Second term , T2 = ?  fifth term , T5 = ?  But nth term of an A.P, Tn = a(n-1)d  T2 = a+(2-1)d  T2 =  a+d  T5 = a + (5 - 1)d  T5 = a +4d  T2 + T5  a+d + a + 4d  2a + 5d = 42.....(i)  T6  = a+ (6- 1)d   = a+ 5d  T3 = a + (3-1)d   = a + 2d  From the question T6- T3 = 12  (a+ 5d) - (a + 2d) = 12  5d - 2d = 12  3d = 12  d = 12/3  d = 4  a, common difference , d = 4","marks":"5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2006>SECTION A>1>b","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : SEQUENCES AND SERIES","question":"The sum of the 2nd and 5t terms of an arithmetic progression (A.P) is 42. If the difference between the 6th and 3rd terms is 12, find the:  First term","images":[],"marking_scheme":"put d = 4 into equation (l)  2a + 5(4) = 42  2a  = 42 - 20  2a = 22  a = 11  first term, a = 11","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2006>SECTION A>1>c","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : SEQUENCES AND SERIES","question":"The sum of the 2nd and 5t terms of an arithmetic progression (A.P) is 42. If the difference between the 6th and 3rd terms is 12, find the:  20th term","images":[],"marking_scheme":"20th term  = T20 = ?  T20 = a + (20-1)d   = 11 + 19(4)   = 87  20th term  = 87","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2006>SECTION A>2","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"2","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : INDICES AND LOGARITHMIC FUNCTIONS","question":"if 22x-3y = 32 and logyx = 2, find the values of x and y    Leave your answer in this format '+x,-y'","images":[],"marking_scheme":"22x-3y = 32  22x-3y = 25  2x - 3y = 5........(i)  Logyx = 2  x = y2.......(ii)  Put x = y2 into equation  (i)  2(y2) - 3y = 5  2y2 - 3y = 5  2y2 - 3y = 5  2y2 - 3y  - 5 = 0  product : 2x - 5 = - 10    Sum  = -3  Two numbers whose product is -10 and whose sum is -3 are -5 and 2  2y2 + 2y - 5y - 5 = 0  2y(y + 1) - 5 (y + 1) = 0  (2y - 5) (y+ 1) = 0  2y - 5  = 0 or y + 1 = 0   2y = 5 or y = -1  y = 5/2 or y = 1  y = 2 1/2 or  - 1  when y = 5/2  x = ( 5/2 )2  x = 25/4  x = 6 1/4  When y = - 1  x = (-1)2  x = 1  when x = 6 1/4, y = 2 1/2 and when x = +1, y = - 1.","marks":"10","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2006>SECTION A>3>a","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : POLYNOMIAL FUNCTIONS","question":"If (x+2) and (x-1) are factor of f(x) = 6x4 + mx3 - 13x2 + nx + 14, find the:    value of m and n    Leave your answer in this format 'm,n'","images":[],"marking_scheme":"(x+ 2) and (x-1) are factors of f(x) = 6x4 + mx3 - 13x2 + nx + 14  Since x + 2 is a factor , the f (-2) = 0  f(-2) = 6(-2)4 + m (-2)3 - 13(-2)2 + n(-2) + 14  6(16) + m(-8) - 13(4) + n(-2) + 14 = 0  96 - 8m - 52 - 2n + 14  8m - 2n + 58 = 0  58 = 8m + 2n  divide through 2  29 = 4m + n  29 = 44m + n  n + 4m = 29.......(i)  Also, since x - 1 is a factor , then f(i) = 0  6(1)4 + m(1)3 - 13(1) + n(1) + 14 = 0  6 +m - 13+ n + 14 = 0  m + n + 7 = 0  m + n = -7 ......(ii)  From equation (ii)  n =  - 7 -m ......(iii)  Put n = - 7 - m into equation (i)   - 7 -m + 4m = 29  3m = 29 + 7  3m = 36  m = 36/3  m  = 12  put m = 12 into the equation (iii)  n  =  - 7 - 12  n = - 19","marks":"5","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2006>SECTION A>3>b","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : POLYNOMIAL FUNCTIONS","question":"If (x+2) and (x-1) are factor of f(x) = 6x4 + mx3 - 13x2 + nx + 14, find the:  remainder when f(x) is divided by (x+1)","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Hence , the polynomial   F(x) = 6x4 + 12x3 -13x2 - 19x  + 14   Let x + 1 = 0  x =  -1  F(-1)gives the remainder of the polynomial   F(-1) = 6(-1)4 + 12(-1)3 - 13(-1)2 - 19(-1) + 14   = 6(1) + 12(-1) - 13(1) + 19 +14   = 6-12-13+19+14  f(-1) = 14  Remainder = 14","marks":"5","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2006>SECTION A>4","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"4","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : DIFFERENTIATION","question":"Find the equation of tangent to curve y = x-1/2x+1, x\u2260 -1/2. at he point (1,0)      Leave your answer in this format 'ay-bx+c=0'","images":[],"marking_scheme":"y=x-12x+1  At point (1,0)the curve and the tangent have the same gradient  Gradient, m =dy/dx  Let u = x- 1, v = 2x+ 1  using quotien rule  ydx=Vdu/dx-Udv/dxV2  dydx=(2x+1)(1)-(x-1)(2)(2x)2   = 2x+1-(2x-2)/(2x+1)2  m=dydx=3(2x+1)2  At (1,0) the gradient of the tanget  m=3(2(1)+1)2=3/(2+1)2= 3/32= 3/9 = 1/3  The equation of  aline passing through a point is given as   m = y-y1/x-x1  (x1,y1) = (1,0)  ; m= 1/3  13=y-0x-1  1(x-1) = 3y  x- 1 = 3y   0 = 3y - x + 1  The equation of the tangent to the curve  3y - x + 1 = 0","marks":"10","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2006>SECTION A>5>a","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : PERMUTATION AND COMBINATIONS.","question":"There are 6 point in a plane. how many triangles can be formed with the points?","images":[],"marking_scheme":"In this case , three point are to be selected from six points since a triangle has three  6C3=6!(6-3)!3!  6!3!3!   =6x5x4x3!3!x3!x2= 20   20 Triangles can be formed.","marks":"5","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2006>SECTION A>5>b","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : PERMUTATION AND COMBINATIONS.","question":"A family of 6 is to be seated in a row , In how many ways can this be done, If the father and mother are not to sit together?    Leave your answer in whole number 'abc'","images":[],"marking_scheme":"If the father and the mother are not to sit together, the children are to be arranged first then he parents are meant to occupy the spces between tthe children  .A.B.C.D.  ABCD are the children and thy can be arranged in 4! ways . the dots represents the position of the parents. There are 5 position for the faher to occupy , then 4 posistion for the mother.= 4! x 5 x 4= 4x3x2x1x5x4 = 480 ways","marks":"5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2006>SECTION A>6","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"6","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY : STATISTICS","question":"The table shows the distribution of the ages of a group of people in a village.  Ages(in years) 15-1819-22 23-26 27-30 31-34 35-38Frequency 40 33 25 10 8 4  using an assumed mean of 24.5, calculate the mean distribution.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Assume mean , Am = 24.5  Agesfxd = x -Amfd15-184016.5-8.0-32019-223320.5-4.0-132.23-62524.50.0027.301028.54.04031-34832.58.06435-38436.512.048  x=Lower class limit + upper class limit2  i.e x  =  15+18/2 x  = 33/2 = 16.5  \u2211f = = 120,\u2211fd = -300  Mean,x=Am+\u2211fd\u2211f   =24.5+(-300)120= 24.5 - 2.5  mean  = 22.0","marks":"10","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2006>SECTION A>7>a","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"VECTORS AND MECHANICS : THE CONCEPTS OF MOTION","question":"A body of mass 5kg resting on a smooth horizontal plane, is acted upon by force 6i + 2j, 5i + 4j and 4i - j. calculate the:    velocity of the body","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Mass , m = 5kg  Resultant force, f = (6i + 2j)  + (5i + 4j)  + (4i - j)= (6+5+4)i  + (2+4-1)j  F = 15i + 5j  From Newton second law of motion   F=m\u2206Vt  F=m(v-u)t  where u = 0ms-1  F=mxt  V=ftm  v=Ftm  v=(15i+15j)t2  v = 3ti + tj","marks":"5","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2006>SECTION A>7>b","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"","topic":"VECTORS AND MECHANICS : THE CONCEPTS OF MOTION","question":"A body of mass 5kg resting on a smooth horizontal plane, is acted upon by force 6i + 2j, 5i + 4j and 4i - j. calculate the:  magnitude of its velocity, after 4 seconds","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Velocity , V after 4s   v = 3(4)i + 4j  V = 12i +4j","marks":"5","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2006>SECTION A>8>a","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"VECTORS AND MECHANICS : PROJECTILES","question":"An object is projected vertically upward with a velocity of 80ms-1. Find the;    Maximum height reached    Leave your answer in whole number 'abc'","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Maximum height, h  Recall v2 = u2 -2gh  02 = 802 - 2(10)h  0 = 6400 - 20h  20h = 6400  h = 6400/20  h = 320 m","marks":"5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2006>SECTION A>8>b","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"VECTORS AND MECHANICS : PROJECTILES","question":"An object is projected vertically upward with a velocity of 80ms-1. Find the;  Time taken to return to the point of projection  [take g = 10ms-2]","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Time taken to reach maximum height , t  V = u - gt  0 = 80 - 10t  10t =80  t= 80/10 = 8s  Since it takes 8s to reach maximum height it will also take 8s to return to the point of rojection hence , total is 16s","marks":"5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2006>SECTION B>9>a","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : SURDS","question":"Simplify\u221a75 - 3\u221a3 + 1,leavingyouanswersin  form a+b\u221ac , where a, b and c are rational numbers.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"To ratioanlise \u221a75 - 3\u221a3 +1,multiply both the numberator and the denominator by the conjugate of the denominator, which is \u221a3 - 1  \u221a75 - 3\u221a3 - 1x\u221a3 - 1\u221a3 - 1  (\u221a25x3 - 3)(\u221a3 - 1)(\u221a3 + 1)(\u221a3 - 1)  (5\u221a3 - 3)(\u221a3 - 1)(\u221a3 + 1)(\u221a3 - 1)  (5\u221a3)(\u221a3) - 5\u221a3(1) - 3\u221a3 + 3\u221a3(\u221a3)-\u221a3+\u221a3 - 1  15-8\u221a3+32  18-8\u221a32  9-4\u221a3","marks":"5","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2006>SECTION B>9>b>i","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : CO-ORDINATE GEOMETRY OF CONIC SECTIONS","question":"The point (7,3), (2,8) and (-3,3) lie on a circle. find the    equation","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Give point (7,3),(2,8) and (-3,3) on a circle using the general equation of a circle   x2 + y2 + 2gx + 2fy + c = 0  At point (7,3)  72 + 32 + 2g(7) + 2f(3) + c = 0  49 + 9 + 14g + 6f + c = 0  58 + 14g + 6f + c = 0  14g + 6f + c = -58  At point  (2,8)  22 + 82 + 2g(2) + 2f(8) + c = 0  4 + 64 + 4g + 16f + c = 0   68 + 4g + 16f + c = 0  4g + 16f + c = -68 ........  At point (-3,3)  (-3)2 + 32 + 2g(-3) + 2f(3) + c = 0  9+9-6g +6f + c = 0  18-6g + 6f + c =0  -6g + 6f + c = -18  -6g + 6f + c = -18 ....(iii)  Substract ewuation (ii) from (i)  10g - 10f = 10  Divide thrugh by 10  g - f = 1.......(iv)  Substrate equation (iii) from (ii)  10g + 10f = -50  Divide thrugh by 10  g+f = -5.....(v)  Add equation (iv) from (v)   = 2g = 4  g=-42  g = -2    Put g = -2 into equation (iv)  -2-f = 1  F = -3  Put g =  2 and f = -3 into equation (i)  14(2) + 6 (-3) + c = -58  -28 - 18 + c = -58  c = -58 + 28 + 18  c = -12  Substitiute g = -2, f = -3 and c = -12 into the general equation of a circle  x2 + y2 + 2(-2)x + 2(-3)y   12 = 0  x2 + Y2 - 4x - 6y - 12 = 0","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2006>SECTION B>9>b>ii","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : CO-ORDINATE GEOMETRY OF CONIC SECTIONS","question":"The point (7,3), (2,8) and (-3,3) lie on a circle. find the   radius of the circle","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Radius , rof the circle   x2 - 4x + 2(-2)2 + y2 - 6y = 12  make  x2 - 4x and y2 - 6 perfected square and add what makes them perfect square to the right hand side.  x2  - 4x + (-4/2)2 + y2 - 6y + (-6/2) = 12 + (4/2)2 + (-6/2)2  x2 - 4x + (-2)2 + y2 - 6y + (-3)2 = 12 + (-2)2 + (-3)2  (x-2)2 + (y - 3)2 = 12 + 4 + 9  (x- 2 )2 + (y - 3)2 = 25  Cmpare with the equation of a circle   (x-a)2  + (y-b)2 = r2  r2 = 25  r = \u221a25  r = 5 unit","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2006>SECTION B>10>a","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : DIFFERENTIATION","question":"The gradient of the targent to the curve y = 4x3 at points P and Q is 108. find the coordinates of P and Q","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Given a curve y = 4x3  Gradient ,m = dy/dx  But ,m = 108  Dy/dx = 12x2  12x2 = 108  x2 = 108/12  x2 = 9  x = \u221a9  x =\u2213 3  When x = 3  y = 4(3)3  y = 4 x 27  y = 108  When x = -3  y = 4(-3)3  y = 4 x -27  y = -108  The coordinates of p and Q are P(3,108) and Q(-3,-108)","marks":"5","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2006>SECTION B>10>b>i","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : TRIGONOMETRY","question":"Given A\u0302 = 45\u2218, B\u0302 = 30\u2218, sin(A+B) = sinAcosB + sinBcosA and cos(A+B) = cosAcosB - sinAsinB    showthat:sin15\u2218=\u221a6 - \u221a24andcos15\u2218=\u221a6 + \u221a24","images":[],"marking_scheme":"A\u0302 = 45\u2218, B\u0302 = 30\u2218  Where Sin(A + B) = SinAcosB +SinBcosA  cos (A+B) = CosA CosB - SinAsinB  To show thatsin15=\u221a6-\u221a24  Sin 15 = sin(45-30) = Sin 45cos30 - sin30cos45  Sin15=(\u221a22x\u221a32)-(12x\u221a22)   =\u221a64-\u221a24  sin15=\u221a6-\u221a24proven  ToshowthatCos15=\u221a6+\u221a24  Cos 15 = cos (45 - 30) = cos(45+(-30))  But cos(-30) = cos30  Sin (-30) = -sin30  Sin15=\u221a22x\u221a\u221a32-\u221a22x12  Cos15=\u221a64+\u221a24  cos15=\u221a+\u221a24","marks":"3","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2006>SECTION B>10>b>ii","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : TRIGONOMETRY","question":"Given A\u0302 = 45\u2218, B\u0302 = 30\u2218, sin(A+B) = sinAcosB + sinBcosA and cos(A+B) = cosAcosB - sinAsinB  Hence find tan 15\u2218","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Tan 15  ButTanA=SinACosA  Tan15=sin15cos15  \u221a6-\u221a24\u00f7\u221a6+\u221a24=\u221a6-\u221a2\u221a6+\u221a2  Rationalize the surd by ,multiplying by multiplying the denominator by \u221a6-\u221a2 which is the conjugate \u221a6 + \u221a2  (\u221a6-\u221a2)(\u221a6+\u221a2)x(\u221a6-\u221a)(\u221a6-\u221a2)   =6-\u221a12-\u221a12+26-\u221a12+\u221a12-2  8-2\u221a124  8-2(2)\u221a34  Tan 15 = 2 -\u221a3","marks":"2","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2006>SECTION B>11>a","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : INTEGRATION","question":"UsingthesubstitutionU=5-x2.evaluate\u222b12x\u221a5-x2dx","images":[],"marking_scheme":"\u222b12x\u221a5-x2dx  using susbstitution u = 5-x2  \u222b14x\u221audx  du/dx = -2x  Du = - 2xdx  When x= 1  u = 5 - 1 = 4  When x = 2  u = 5-22  u = 5-4  u = 1  dx =-du2x  \u222b14x\u221au.-du2x  \u222b14 - du/2\u221au  1/2\u222b14 U-1/2du  -1/2(u-1/2+1-1/2+1)14  1/2(U1/2 x 2/1)14  1/2(2U1/2)14  -(\u221au)14  [\u221a1 - \u221a4]  - [1-2]  - [-1]= 1","marks":"5","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2006>SECTION B>11>b","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : DIFFERENTIATION","question":"Ifp=px2+qx,dydx=7andd2ydx2=6.findthevaluesofpandq","images":[],"marking_scheme":"dydx=2px+q  d2y/dx2 = 2p  But dy/dx = 2p  But dy/dx = 7  2px + q = 7 .....(i)  Also, d2y/dx2 = 6  2p = 6  p = 6/2 = 3  put p = 3 in equ 1  2(3)x + q = 7  q = 7 - 6x  p = 3 and q = 7 - 6x","marks":"5","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2006>SECTION B>13>a","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY : PROBABILITY","question":"A man p has 5 red, and 3 blue  and 2 white buses. Another man Q has 3 red, 2 blue and 4 white buses. A bus owned by p is involved in an accident with bus belonging to Q. calculate the probability that the two buses are not the same colour.    Leave your answer in this format 'a/b'","images":[],"marking_scheme":"For a man   Red Rp = 5  Blu, Bp  3  White , Wp = 2  Total  = 5+3+2 = 10  for  a man Q  Red RQ = 3  Blue,BQ = 2  White ,WQ = 4  Total = +2+4 = 9  Probability that they are not the same colour= Pr(Rp) x Pr(BQ) + Pr(Rp) x Pr(WQ) + Pr(Bp) x Pr(RQ) + Pr(Rp) x Pr(WQ) + Pr(Wp) x Pr(RQ) + Pr(Wp) x Pr(BQ)  =510x29+510x49+310x39+310x49+310x49+210x39  =1090+2090+990+1290+690+490=   61/90","marks":"5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2006>SECTION B>13>b","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : PERMUTATION AND COMBINATIONS.","question":"A man travels from Nigeria to ghana by air abd from ghana to liberia by ship. He returns by the same means . he has 6 airlines and  4 shipping lines to choose from. in how many ways can he make his journey without using the same airline or shipping line twice ?","images":[],"marking_scheme":"For his movement i.e from Nigeria to Ghana, he is to select one airline from six airlines, and from Ghana to liberia, he is to select one shipping line from 4 shipping lines. that is 6C1 X 4C1  =6!(6-1)!1!x4!(4-1)!1!  =6!5!1!x4!3!=6x5!5!x4x3!3!   The same 24 ways for his journey , which means 24 for to and 24 for fro.= 24 x 24= 576 ways","marks":"5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2006>SECTION B>14>a","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY : STATISTICS","question":"The table below shows the distribution of hours spent at work by the employee of a factor in a week.  Time(hours) 20-29 30-39 40-49 50-59 60-69 70-79no of persons 8 11 23 25 8 5    Draw a ogive for the distribution","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Time(hours)Frequency  cummulative frequency upper boundary20-298829.530-39111939.540-49234249.550-59256759.560-6987569.570-7958079.5","marks":"3","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2006>SECTION B>14>b>i","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY : STATISTICS","question":"Using your graph, estimate the    median    Leave your answer in one decimal place ab.c","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Median=(n+12)thedata  80+12  812= 40.5th data= 40.5th data   From the graph , the median is 48.8hrs","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2006>SECTION B>14>b>ii","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY : STATISTICS","question":"Using your graph, estimate the   lower quartile;","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Lowerquartile,Q1=(n+14)thdata  Q1=(80+14)= 20.25th data   Q1 = 40hrs (from the graph)","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2006>SECTION B>14>b>iii","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"iii","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY : STATISTICS","question":"Using your graph, estimate the   40th percentile","images":[],"marking_scheme":"40th percentile  =40100x80= 32nd data  From the graph, 40th percentile is 45.5hrs","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2006>SECTION B>14>b>iv","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"iv","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY : STATISTICS","question":"Using your graph, estimate the   number of employees that spent at least 50 hours 30 minutes","images":[],"marking_scheme":"At least 50hr 30min = 32   32 employee spent at least 50hr 30min","marks":"1","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2006>SECTION B>15>a","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY : PROBABILITY","question":"Two pupils are chosen at random from a group of 4 boys and girls. Find the probability that the two pupils chosen would be boys.    Leave your answer in fraction 'a/b'","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Boys  , B = 4  Girls, G = 5  Sample space , s.s = 4+ 5 = 9  Pr(two pupils are boys ) = Pr(first pupil is a boy) and Pr(second pupil is a boy )= Pr(B) x Pr(B)   =49x38  =16","marks":"2","difficulty":"1"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2006>SECTION B>15>b>i","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY : PROBABILITY","question":"Twenty percent of the total production of transistors produced by a machine are below standard. if a random sample of 6 transistors produced by the machine is taken , what is the probability of getting;    exactly 2    Leave your answer in five decimal places 'a.bcdef'","images":[],"marking_scheme":"P =20% = 20/100  =15Below standard  Q=80%=80100=45Standard  ButnCr=n!(n-r)!r!  Where n = 6 , r = 2  Pr(r) = nCr qrPn-r (standard)  Pr(2)=6C2(45)2(15)4  =6!(6-2)!2!.1615(15)4  =6x5x4!4x2!(1625)(15)4= 0.01536","marks":"2","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2006>SECTION B>15>b>ii","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY : PROBABILITY","question":"Twenty percent of the total production of transistors produced by a machine are below standard. if a random sample of 6 transistors produced by the machine is taken , what is the probability of getting;  exactly 1    Leave your answer in six decimal places 'a.bcdefg'","images":[],"marking_scheme":"r = 1 , n = 6  Pr(1)=6C5(45)1(15)5  6!(6-1)!1!(45)(15)5  6x55!(45)(15)5  6(45)(15)5= 0.001536","marks":"2","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2006>SECTION B>15>b>iii","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"iii","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY : PROBABILITY","question":"Twenty percent of the total production of transistors produced by a machine are below standard. if a random sample of 6 transistors produced by the machine is taken , what is the probability of getting;  at least 2    Leave your answer in five decimal places 'a.bcdef'","images":[],"marking_scheme":"PR(at least 2 standard resistors) = Pr(2) +Pr(3) + pr + Pr(5) + Pr (6), which is he same as   1-Pr(less than 2 resistor below standard)  Pr(r\u22652) =  1 - [PR(0) + Pr(1)]= 1- [6C0 (1/5)0 + (4/5)6 + 6C1(4/5)5]= 1 - [6!/(6-0)! (4/5)6 + 6!/(6-1)! (1/5)(4/5)5] = 1 - [(4/5)6 + 6(1/5)(4/5)5] = 1 - 0.65536 = 0.34464","marks":"2","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2006>SECTION B>15>b>iv","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"iv","group":"FINAL","topic":"STATISTICS AND PROBABILITY : PROBABILITY","question":"Twenty percent of the total production of transistors produced by a machine are below standard. if a random sample of 6 transistors produced by the machine is taken , what is the probability of getting;  At most 2, standard transistor(s)?      Leave your answer in five decimal places 'a.bcdef'","images":[],"marking_scheme":"Pr(at most 2 standard resistors)= Pr(0) + Pr(1) + Pr(2)= 6C0 ( 4/5 )0( 1/5 )6 + 6C1( 4/5 ) + 6C2 (4/5)2(1/5)4 = 6!/6!(1)(1/5)6 + 6!/5! (4/5)(1/5) + 6!/4!2! (4/2)2(1/5)4= (1/5)6 + 6!/5! (4/5)(1/5)5 + 6!/4!2! (4/5)2(1/5)4=(1/5)6 + 6(4/5)(1/5)5 + 5(4/5)2(1/5)4= 0.01696","marks":"2","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2006>SECTION B>16>a","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"VECTORS AND MECHANICS : STATICS","question":"A body of mass 15 kg is suspended at a point p by two light inextensible strings XP \u2192 and YP\u2192. The strings are icnlined at 60\u2218 and 40\u2218 respectively to the downward vertical. Find , correct to two decima placs the tension in the string. [take g = 10ms-2]","images":["data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"150Sin100=T1sin140  T1=150Sin140sin100  T1 = 97.91N  Similarly  150sin100=T2sin120  T2=150sin120sin100  T2 = 131.91N","marks":"5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2006>SECTION B>16>b>i","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : DIFFERENTIATION","question":"The height h metres, of a ball thrown into the air is 2+20t+kt2, after t seconds. if its take 2 seconds for the ball to reach its highest point find,    The value of k;","images":[],"marking_scheme":"h = 2 + 20t + kt2  At maximum height point , final velocity, v = 0ms-1  wherev=ddt  dh/dt = 0+20+2kt  Hence , 20+2k+2kt = 0  But it takes 2s to reach it highest point  20 + 2k(2) = 0  4k = -20  k=-204  k = -5","marks":"3","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2006>SECTION B>16>b>ii","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"PURE MATHEMATICS : DIFFERENTIATION","question":"The height h metres, of a ball thrown into the air is 2+20t+kt2, after t seconds. if its take 2 seconds for the ball to reach its highest point find,  its highest point from the point of throw.","images":[],"marking_scheme":"h = 2 + 20t + kt2  But it takes 2s to get to the higest point  h = 2+20(2) + (-5)(2)2  h = 2 + 40 + (-5)(4)  h = 2+40-20  h = 22m","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2006>SECTION B>17>a","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"VECTORS AND MECHANICS : THE IMPULSE AND MOMENTUM EQUATIONS","question":"A ball P moving with velocity 2u ms-1, collides with a similar ball Q, of different mass, which is at rest. After collision, Q moves with u ms-1 amd P with velocity 1/2 u ms-1, in the opposite direction. Find the ratio of the mass of P and Q    Leave your answer in this format 'a:b'","images":["data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Using the principles of conversation of linear momentum   M1 + 2u + m2 x0 = -1/2u x m1 + m2 x u  2um1 + 0=  - 1/2 + um2  2um1/1 + uM1 = Um2  4um1+um1/2  2um2  5um1 = 2um2  Divide both sides 5um*%2*:  5um15um2=2um25m2  M1m2=25  Therefore the ratio of mass of p and Q s 2:5.","marks":"5","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2006>SECTION B>17>b","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"b","group":"FINAL","topic":"VECTORS AND MECHANICS : STATICS","question":"Two forces of magnitude 3 N and 7 N have a resultant of magnitude of 5N calculate, correct to one decimalthe place , the angle between the two force.","images":["data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"The angles between 3N and 7N must be obtuse since their resultant is less than force     This is from the parallelogram of vector addition    Using coine rule  52 = 72 + 32 - 2(7)(3) cos(80-\u03b8)=  25  49 + 9 - 42cos(180 - \u03b8)= 42Cos(180-\u03b8) = 33  Cos(180-\u03b8) = 0.7857  180 - \u03b8 = cos-1 0.7857  180 - \u03b8 = 38.2  180 - 38.2 = \u03b8  \u03b8 = 141.8","marks":"3","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2006>SECTION B>17>c","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"c","group":"","topic":"VECTORS AND MECHANICS : VECTORS","question":"AB\u2192=-46andCB\u219223are two vectors in the XY plane .If V is the mid-point AB\u2192. find CV\u2192","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"AB\u2192=-46CB\u219223    AC\u2192 + CB\u2192 = AB\u2192  =-46-23  AC\u2192=-4,-26-,(-3)  AC\u2192=-69  But AV = 1/2 AB\u2192   =-12-46  AV=-23  Also AC\u2192 + CV\u2192 = AV\u2192  CV\u2192 = AV\u2192 - AC\u2192   =23--69   =-2+63-9  CV\u2192=4-6","marks":"2","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2006>SECTION B>18>a","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"a","group":"FINAL","topic":"VECTORS AND MECHANICS : THE CONCEPTS OF MOTION","question":"A body of mass 5kg is placed on a smooth plane inclined at an angle 30\u2218 to the horizontal. Find the magnitude of the force    Acting parallel to plane;","images":["data:image/png;base64,","data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"- The force parallel to the plan is mg sin\u03b8. This is the force which makes the body to slide down the plan  F = mgsin \u03b8= 5 x 10sin30= 50 x 0.5= 25N    - The force to keep the body in equilibrm is a horizontal force     Force \u03b8 = mgsin\u03b8  F=mgSin\u03b8cos\u03b8  F = mgTan\u03b8  F = mgTan\u03b8  F  50 x 0.5774 = 28.87N","marks":"5","difficulty":"2"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2006>SECTION B>18>b>i","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"i","group":"FINAL","topic":"VECTORS AND MECHANICS : STATICS","question":"A uniform plank PQ of length 10m and mass m kg  rests on two support A and B. where \\PA\\ = \\BQ\\ = 1m. A load of mass 8kg is placed on the plank at point C such that \\AC\\ = 3.5 m. If the reaction at B is 100N calculate the    value of m","images":["data:image/png;base64,"],"marking_scheme":"Taking moment, sum of clockwise mmoent  = sum of anticlockwise moment  80(4.5-1) + 10m(5-1) = 100(9-1)  80 x 3.5 + 10m x 4 = 100 x 8  280 + 40m = 800  40 = 520  m=52040  m = 13kg.","marks":"3","difficulty":"3"},{"id":"theory>Further Maths>2006>SECTION B>18>b>ii","subject":"Further Maths","year":"2006","type":"Theory","sub_label":"ii","group":"FINAL","topic":"VECTORS AND MECHANICS : STATICS","question":"A uniform plank PQ of length 10m and mass m kg  rests on two support A and B. where \\PA\\ = \\BQ\\ = 1m. A load of mass 8kg is placed on the plank at point C such that \\AC\\ = 3.5 m. If the reaction at B is 100N calculate the  reaction at A. [take g = 10ms-2]","images":[],"marking_scheme":"For translational equilibrium,  Sum of vertical upward force must be equal to the sum of vertical downward force.    R + 100 = 80 + (10 x 13)  R + 100 = 80 + 130  R + 100 = 210  R = 210 - 100  R = 110N","marks":"2","difficulty":"3"}];